    {
      "leftTitle": "Step 3",
      "rightTitle": "Eq. 9",
      "left": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Now substitute the stationary density from Eq. 9. This is where the piecewise split enters."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The Heaviside factor keeps only the stable locked half of phase space."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "H(\\cos\\theta)\\;\\Rightarrow\\; -\\pi/2 \\le \\theta \\le \\pi/2",
          "displayMode": true
        }
      ],
      "right": [
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\rho = \\begin{cases}\\delta\\!\\left[\\theta-\\psi-\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right] H(\\cos\\theta), & |\\omega| < Kr \\\\ \\frac{C}{\\left|\\omega-Kr\\sin(\\theta-\\psi)\\right|}, & \\text{elsewhere.}\\end{cases}",
          "displayMode": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "leftTitle": "Step 4",
      "rightTitle": "Eq. 10",
      "left": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Split the integral into locked and drifting contributions. The locked delta term collapses the phase integral onto the synchronized phase, while the drifting branch stays as a continuous density."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\int f(\\theta)\\,\\delta(\\theta-\\theta_*)\\,d\\theta = f(\\theta_*)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "This identity says the delta does not leave a broad theta-density behind. It samples the rest of the integrand at the one phase where the delta argument is zero."
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "value": "So a large theta value does not make the locked contribution large. It contributes zero unless theta exactly matches the locked phase selected by the delta."
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "\\theta_* = \\psi + \\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)",
              "displayMode": true
            },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "That difference is visible directly in Eq. 10. The locked term still shows d theta d omega, but the delta factor means the theta integral is only formal: it picks out theta = theta star, so after carrying it out only the omega integration really remains."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\int_{-\\pi/2}^{\\pi/2} F(\\theta,\\omega)\\,\\delta\\!\\left[\\theta-\\theta_*(\\omega)\\right] d\\theta = F(\\theta_*(\\omega),\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "By contrast, the drifting term has no delta. Instead it contains a continuous weight built from C, g of omega, and the denominator absolute value of omega minus K r sine of theta minus psi. It also keeps the full phase range from minus pi to pi, so that second term is a genuine two-variable integral over both theta and omega."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Putting those two pieces together gives Eq. 10."
        }
      ],
